snippet.textDisplay: I've already commented here that I am content to wait to watch this movie on Disney+, which is part of the reason I get the 1 year subscription.  However here is a potentially controversial opinion: I would be curious to see the episode IX that Rian Johnson was going to make based upon his set up, to see where he was going; I would also like to see the episodes VIII and IX that Abrams originally had loosely sketched out; and I would like to see the episodes VII, VIII and IX that George Lucas had conceived of as his third act.  Of course this might be a byproduct of my belief that Copyright terms are way to long and need to be much shorter... or it may be a response to the fact that I didn't hate "The Last Jedi", I thought it was flawed but not unwatchable drivel, and that having seen it the first time after six months of YouTube recommendations from people who loathed the movie.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wow. Shouldn’t we start calling it fan disservice?

Such nostalgia bits kill a movie for me, and it sounds like this one is going to be downright nauseating.

Using what we know and adding to or deepening it takes subtlety and skill in storytelling, but regurgitating with a wink is awful pandering. The Mandalorian has given examples of both. Seeing Jawas defend their sandcrawler was amazing! Seeing Mando communicate with Tusken Raiders was great and aligned with the village side of them we saw in Attack of the Clones. But going to the MOs Eisley cantina? Sitting in Han’s spot? My eyes are still recovering from the amount of rolling .
